rest. His only medication is ramipril. He will require a medication to minimise his risk of clotting for three months after the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin","Aspirin","Aspirin and clopidogrel","Rivaroxaban","Dabigatran"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients undergoing any form of cardiac valve replacement will require some form of antithrombotic therapy after the procedure to minimize the risk of clotting post-procedure. The patient\u0027s symptoms, including syncopal episodes and worsening dyspnea, indicate the severity of his aortic stenosis and the necessity for careful consideration of antithrombotic therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin - \u003C/strong\u003EIn patients undergoing transcatheter aortic valve implantation (TAVI), recent evidence has shown that single therapy with \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin\u003C/strong\u003E has shown to be more effective than dual antiplatelet or additional anticoagulant therapies, provided the patient does not have any special indications for anticoagulation such as atrial fibrillation. Single antiplatelet therapy with aspirin proved to be non-inferior in the prevention of ischaemic events and superior in avoiding haemorrhagic events compared to dual antiplatelet therapy with aspirin plus clopidogrel. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual Antiplatelet Therapy (Aspirin + Clopidogrel) - \u003C/strong\u003EDual antiplatelet therapy\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis not preferred in this case as in patients who do not require anticoagulant therapy, single therapy with aspirin is more favorable than dual antiplatelet therapy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin - \u003C/strong\u003EWarfarin is not recommended as the first choice for antithrombotic therapy post-TAVI, as there are ongoing debates regarding the use of vitamin K antagonists like warfarin and direct-acting anticoagulants (DOACs) with inconclusive results, hence it is not recommended. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban and Dabigatran -\u003C/strong\u003E The usage of direct-acting anticoagulants like rivaroxaban or dabigatran post-TAVI shows inconclusive results from comparison studies between vitamin K antagonists and DOACs. The lack of a clear consensus suggests that these agents may not be the preferred option in the absence of specific indications such as atrial fibrillation.  \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aspirin monotherapy is the current recommended regimen for antithrombotic therapy after transcatheter aortic valve implantation (TAVI), provided there are no specific indications such as atrial fibrillation."],"references":["Gatto L, Scalia L. The temptation of anticoagulant therapy after transcatheter aortic valve implantation. European Heart Journal Supplements. 2023 Apr 1;25(Supplement_B):B95-8. Available from: https://academic.oup.com/eurheartjsupp/article/25/Supplement_B/B95/7135766"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25654"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25654"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-12-14T21:33:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T08:30:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2040"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi